Third-party components
----------------------

The packaged macOS application bundles third-party software in three layers: a
CPython interpreter, the Python dependency wheels, and the Rust crates compiled
into the native shell.

Bundled runtime — CPython
-------------------------

- **CPython** (3.12.x, via the python-build-standalone redistribution) — the
  embedded Python interpreter that runs the server and engines. Python Software
  Foundation License (PSF-2.0). Its verbatim LICENSE is collected into
  `THIRD-PARTY-LICENSES/cpython/` at build time. The standalone build itself is
  published under the PSF/MIT terms documented at
  https://github.com/astral-sh/python-build-standalone

Python dependency wheels
------------------------

The bundled Python dependencies are pinned in
`requirements/requirements-bundle.txt`; most are MIT, BSD, or Apache 2.0. The
components below carry copyleft or otherwise attribution-required licenses and
are called out explicitly:

- **python-soxr** (soxr 1.1.0) — Python bindings for libsoxr, the SoX
  Resampler Library. GNU Lesser General Public License v2.1 or later
  (LGPL-2.1+). Source: https://github.com/dofuuz/python-soxr
- **pycountry** (26.2.16) — ISO country/subdivision data. GNU Lesser General
  Public License v2.1 only (LGPL-2.1-only). Source:
  https://github.com/pycountry/pycountry
- **odfpy** (1.4.1) — OpenDocument (.odt/.ods) reader. The importable `odf`
  library Estormi uses is GNU Lesser General Public License v2.1 or later
  (LGPL-2.1-or-later); the package additionally ships standalone command-line
  tools under GPL-2.0 which Estormi neither bundles in its call path nor
  invokes. Its wheel carries no license file, so the verbatim LGPL-2.1 text is
  vendored at `make/extra-licenses/odfpy/` and collected into the bundle.
  Source: https://github.com/eea/odfpy
- **certifi** (2026.5.20) — Mozilla CA certificate bundle. Mozilla Public
  License 2.0 (MPL-2.0). Source: https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi
- **tqdm** (4.68.2) — progress bars. Mozilla Public License 2.0 and MIT
  (MPL-2.0 AND MIT). Source: https://github.com/tqdm/tqdm
- **pypdfium2** (5.9.0) — Python bindings for Google's PDFium. The bindings are
  Apache-2.0 / BSD-3-Clause; the bundled PDFium binary carries BSD-3-Clause
  plus its own third-party component notices (FreeType, libjpeg, libpng,
  libtiff, zlib, ICU) and CC-BY-4.0 for some data files. Source:
  https://github.com/pypdfium2-team/pypdfium2

User-downloaded models (not redistributed)
-------------------------------------------

Estormi does not ship any model weights. The local briefing/TTS models are
downloaded by the user at runtime from their upstream sources and remain
governed by their own licenses, which the user accepts on download:

- **Ministral-3-14B-Instruct** (Mistral) — Apache-2.0 (default briefing model).
- **Voxtral** mlx-audio TTS (Mistral) — Apache-2.0.
- **Gemma-4-12B-Instruct** (Google) — **Gemma Terms of Use**, a custom non-OSI
  license with use restrictions, NOT Apache-2.0. Opt-in tier.

Rust crates (native shell)
--------------------------

The macOS shell (`apps/estormi-macos/`) statically links Rust crates, declared
in `apps/estormi-macos/Cargo.toml` and pinned in `apps/estormi-macos/Cargo.lock`.
The notable direct dependencies — Tauri (`tauri`, `tauri-plugin-shell`), `axum`,
`tokio`, `reqwest`, `serde`/`serde_json`, `image`, `qrcode`, `sha2`, `chrono`,
`anyhow`, and the `whatsapp-rust`/`wacore` family — are each dual-licensed
MIT OR Apache-2.0 (a small number MIT-only). The authoritative, verbatim
per-crate license and copyright texts are generated from the lockfile with
`make rust-licenses` (which runs `cargo about generate` in `apps/estormi-macos/`),
committed at `apps/estormi-macos/THIRD-PARTY-RUST.md`, and collected into the
bundle at build time.

The license texts for every bundled Python package, the Rust crates, and the
CPython interpreter are collected into
`Estormi.app/Contents/Resources/THIRD-PARTY-LICENSES/` at build time:

- one directory per Python distribution — each wheel's verbatim `LICENSE*` /
  `COPYING*` / `NOTICE*` / `AUTHORS*` file from its `*.dist-info`. When a wheel
  ships no such file (e.g. odfpy, mistral_common, sentencepiece, openpyxl,
  tokenizers, onnxruntime), the build falls back to the wheel's `METADATA`
  license declaration, and any verbatim copyleft text needed to satisfy the
  license (LGPL-2.1 for odfpy) is supplied from the committed
  `make/extra-licenses/` overlay — so no bundled package is omitted;
- `rust/` — the committed `THIRD-PARTY-RUST.md` (all statically-linked crates);
- `cpython/` — the interpreter's `LICENSE.txt`.
